===Etymology===
Borrowed from {{bor|en|fr|mayonnaise}}, possibly named after the city {{w|Maó}}, {{w|Minorca}}, whence the recipe was brought back to France. Alternative suggested origins include the city of {{w|Bayonne}} ({{m|fr|bayonnaise}}); the French word {{m|fr|manier||to handle}}; the Old French {{m|fr|moyeu||egg yolk}}; and the Duke of {{w|Mayenne}}.

